post_text: It is with deepest sympathy that we have to say that Paula Mayo has gone to be with her Savior yesterday after a long battle with cancer. Paula brought so much joy and heart to Winter Wonderland. We would not be where we are today without all of her hard work and dedication. She will very missed. Our thoughts and prayers are with Paula’s family and friends during this difficult time.

post_text:
Below is the 2017 WWOL Christmas Parade Line-up area. Please if you are participating in the parade follow the directions on how to get into your division.

Bands travel Central Avenue and turn on to 16th Street. Fire Trucks travel Lexington Avenue and turn onto 17th Street (toward the river). Divisions 2, 4 & 7 should enter the line-up area by traveling on Greenup Avenue to their assigned street, turn up the designated street, and cross Winchester Avenue to the line-up area. Divisions 5, 8, 9, & 10 should travel Central Avenue to their designated area. Divisions 1, 3, & 6, should enter from 22nd Street and travel up Carter Avenue to their designated area. IF YOU DO NOT FOLLOW THESE DIRECTIONS ON GETTING TO YOUR LINE-UP AREA YOU MORE THAN LIKELY WILL NOT GET IN THE CORRECT DIVISION. Divisions fill up quickly so you must enter the parade line-up as listed above

post_text:
Can't come to the parade, Tuesday, Nov. 22nd watch it live!! A live feed provided by Time Warner Cable will enable you to watch the parade if you can't make it downtown. You may access on 4 different web sites: WLGC Radio; The Independent; Ohio University Southern; and WSAZ TV.

Also, a few fun facts about this year's parade:

This year we have approximately 3,500 participants which does not include:
1. The 4 bands
2. All of the police, fire trucks, emergency vehicles, etc. that participate
3. 3 ROTC units
4. The people driving the vehicles in the parade
5. The people handling the animals (dogs, cats, horses)
6. And the Shriners which encompass an area from Carter Avenue to Central Avenue, one entire city block.

post_text:
I want to answer some questions I have been receiving:
1) Train Rides and Visits with Santa are Friday - Sunday, 6-9 p.m. If you buy a ticket for the train it will run until you get your ride.
2) When you visit Santa, there is no charge. We do have a professional photographer taking picture but you are not required to purchase one, you may take your own but please remember there are other people in line to see Santa.
3) We no longer have the horse and carriage rides the gentleman that provided that service retired.
4) The ice skating rink is no longer open.
5) The location to ride the train and visit with Santa in the Log house in on the 22nd Street end of the park directly across from King's Daughters Medical Center.
6) If you do not want to ride the train to see the lights you may drive around and through the park or walk. Again, there is no charge to view the light displays.

We invite you to come visit us and enjoy the light displays. Merry Christmas!

post_text:
“T’was the Lights Before Christmas” theme for Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival 2015

WSAZ News Channel 3 Anchor Rob Johnson will serve as Master of Ceremonies during the Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival’s Opening Night Ceremony on Monday, November 16, 6 p.m. on the Bandstand in Central Park. There will be: music provided by The Jeff Carter Group and The John Thornsberry Trio; the lighting of the lights by the 2015 Winter Wonderland Queen and her court; and Santa Claus will make an appearance to visit with the children.

The Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival’s annual Christmas parade scheduled for November 24, 7 p.m. in downtown Ashland is now accepting registrations. Registration forms may be obtained by calling 606-324-5111, visiting the Alliance office, 1740 Winchester Avenue or email: paula@ashlandalliance.com. Parade registrations must be received no later than November 18.

There will be cash awards of $500 (1st place), $250 (2nd place) and $100 (3rd place) for the float that best utilize the parade theme in the float competition.
text:
“T’was the Lights Before Christmas” theme for Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival 2015

WSAZ News Channel 3 Anchor Rob Johnson will serve as Master of Ceremonies during the Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival’s Opening Night Ceremony on Monday, November 16, 6 p.m. on the Bandstand in Central Park. There will be: music provided by The Jeff Carter Group and The John Thornsberry Trio; the lighting of the lights by the 2015 Winter Wonderland Queen and her court; and Santa Claus will make an appearance to visit with the children.

The Winter Wonderland of Lights Festival’s annual Christmas parade scheduled for November 24, 7 p.m. in downtown Ashland is now accepting registrations. Registration forms may be obtained by calling 606-324-5111, visiting the Alliance office, 1740 Winchester Avenue or email: paula@ashlandalliance.com. Parade registrations must be received no later than November 18.

There will be cash awards of $500 (1st place), $250 (2nd place) and $100 (3rd place) for the float that best utilize the parade theme in the float competition.

post_text: REALLY, REALLY, need volunteers to help line-up the annual Christmas Parade in downtown Ashland. The parade is scheduled for Tuesday, November 26. Line-up begins at 5 p.m. and I really need the volunteers in their units by 4:30 or 4:45 p.m. PLEASE if you are able to volunteer give me a call at the Ashland Alliance, 324-5111 or on my mobile or email: paula@ashlandalliance.com.

post_text: Winter Wonderland would love to see as many community organizations, businesses, individuals, etc. involved with the festival this year and one way is to design and make a "Christmas Card to the Community". We have churches, girl scouts, boy scouts, area businesses that make a card each year. If you or your group or neighborhood, business, etc. is interested let me know.
